abstract: In Iowa and New Hampshire, it’s Mr. Buttigieg — not Bernie Sanders — who has complicated Ms. Warren’s path, winning over college-educated white voters using a similar message of Democratic unity.
snippet: In Iowa and New Hampshire, it’s Mr. Buttigieg — not Bernie Sanders — who has complicated Ms. Warren’s path, winning over college-educated white voters using a similar message of Democratic unity.
lead_paragraph: MERRIMACK N.H. — In the back row of an event geared toward veterans for Pete Buttigieg, the former mayor of South Bend, Ind., on Thursday, a discussion broke about one of his Democratic rivals — Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts.

abstract: Mr. Buttigieg has picked up the most pledged delegates so far, but it’s early in the race: 1,990 pledged delegates are needed to secure the Democratic presidential nomination.
snippet: Mr. Buttigieg has picked up the most pledged delegates so far, but it’s early in the race: 1,990 pledged delegates are needed to secure the Democratic presidential nomination.
lead_paragraph: MANCHESTER, N.H. — Former Mayor Pete Buttigieg of South Bend, Ind., has taken 13 pledged delegates from Iowa’s maligned caucuses and Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont has won 12, The Associated Press said Friday.

headline_main: Buttigieg Leads Sanders in Iowa Delegates, 13-12. So, Who Won?
headline_print_headline: 40 (or So) Delegates Down, And Nearly 2,000 More to Go
byline_original: By Reid J. Epstein and Matt Stevens

abstract: Joe Biden’s organization remained weak. Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren focused on cities and college towns. Mr. Buttigieg, however, went everywhere.
snippet: Joe Biden’s organization remained weak. Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren focused on cities and college towns. Mr. Buttigieg, however, went everywhere.
lead_paragraph: OELWEIN, Iowa — Two days before the Iowa caucuses, Pete Buttigieg stopped for a town hall event at the Oelwein Coliseum, a 92-year-old music venue that in its heyday hosted the likes of Lawrence Welk and Sammy Kaye.

abstract: In the first presidential primary debate following the messy Iowa caucuses, and days before New Hampshire votes, Bernie Sanders and Pete Buttigieg were tested repeatedly.
snippet: In the first presidential primary debate following the messy Iowa caucuses, and days before New Hampshire votes, Bernie Sanders and Pete Buttigieg were tested repeatedly.
lead_paragraph: MANCHESTER, N.H. — There was neither a soaring nor shattering moment for the Democratic presidential candidates at their debate on Friday night, but it was still the most contentious one yet, and could influence some New Hampshire voters ahead of the state’s primary on Tuesday. Here are seven takeaways from the night.

lead_paragraph: The C-SPAN video from 1995 is grainy, but the audio is clear: Senator Joe Biden is heard bragging about his support for freezing spending on Social Security as part of broader deficit reduction legislation.
